s influential on his own work. Despite this acclaim, the film has largely vanished from the cultural consciousness and few queer people today have even heard of it, let alone seen it.With this new addition to the Queer Film Classics series, Chris Dupuis looks at the disconnect between the film’s historical importance and its subsequent disappearance, examining how the story of Winter Kept Us Warm can serve as a starting point for intergenerational queer dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHomosexuality in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aArthur Zeldin.  aBill C 150.  aCanadian film.  aCannes Film Festival.  aCommonwealth Film Festival.  aDavid Cronenberg.  aDon Owen.  aDouglas LePan.  aFrench New Wave.  aHart House.  aHenry Tarvainen.  aJames Stoller.  aJanet Amos.  aJewish.  aJohn Labow.  aJoy Fielding.  aLarry Kent.  aNFB.  aNobody Waved Goodbye.  aOntario Film Review Board.  aPaul Hoffert.  aTS Eliot.  aToronto.  aUofT.  aWaste Land.  aWinnipeg.  acollaboration.  agay bashing.  algbtqia.  amemory studies.  aqueer history.  astudent film.1 aGreyson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228020349?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228020349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228020349/original  a978-3-11-140848-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles